# naming-conventions.allowlist
#
# Pre-existing violations of the naming-convention rules that the guard
# would otherwise flag. Each entry is one line in the form:
#
#     <file>:<line>:<rule>
#
# Where rule is one of:
#   parseint     — parseInt() without explicit radix
#   sql-alias    — camelCase SQL alias inside db.raw()
#
# Adding to this file is allowed only when:
#   1. The violation is pre-existing (not introduced by your PR), AND
#   2. There is a tracked work item to clean it up.
#
# Removing entries (i.e. fixing the violation) is always welcome.
#
# Lines starting with # and blank lines are ignored.
#
# ─── parseInt without radix (frontend, mostly UI input handlers) ─────────────
# These follow the pattern `parseInt(x) || N`. They will be cleaned up
# opportunistically as the affected components are touched. New code MUST
# use parseInt(x, 10).


# Note: SQL string-form aliases like `as patientId` are widespread and
# runtime-safe (the camelCaseResponse middleware is a no-op for already-
# camelCase keys). The naming guard does NOT flag them. See the comment
# in check-naming-conventions.sh next to Rule 3 for the reasoning.
